title: 8  Solo Project
text:
Between 2015 and 2016, South Africa’s crime landscape was largely shaped by Gauteng, which recorded the highest crime density. As the country’s most densely populated province, home to major urban centers like Johannesburg and Pretoria, Gauteng experienced a significant volume of criminal activities. Following closely behind was the Western Cape, which includes Cape Town—a bustling metropolis and popular tourist destination. This province also faced high crime rates, especially in areas struggling with socioeconomic challenges.
KwaZulu-Natal, known for its large population and expansive coastline, ranked third in crime density. While it still experienced considerable criminal activity, its crime rates were somewhat lower than those of Gauteng and the Western Cape. In contrast, the Northern Cape, the largest yet sparsely populated province, reported the lowest crime density. Its vast size and low population density contributed to fewer reported incidents of crime.
This choropleth map visually highlights the uneven distribution of crime across South African provinces during this period, drawing attention to high-crime regions like Gauteng while also shedding light on provinces with lower crime rates, such as the Northern Cape.

What features would we like a visualization of the categorical difficulty rating variable to capture?

Exercise 2: Load tidyverse

# Use the ggplot function
ggplot(hikes, aes(x = rating))






# Load the package
library(tidyverse)

Exercise 3: Bar chart of ratings
How many hikes fall into each category? dont know yet at this point - look at future plot where the data is added in
Are the hikes evenly distributed among these categories, or are some more common than others? When looking at the new ggpplot below, we see that they are not even. Moderate category was the highest and difficult was the lowest

ggplot(hikes, aes(x = rating))







What did this do? What do you observe? Created a bargraph the splits the rating of difficulty into either easy, difficult and moderate
What, in general, is the first argument of the ggplot() function? the name of the dataset being used
What is the purpose of writing x = rating? assigning a name to the variable/axis, x
What do you think aes stands for?!? aesthetic - telling you what data is being used to create graph
Exercise 4: Bar Chart of Ratings Pt 2

# geom_bar() adds in the data/count axis for the bargraph
ggplot(hikes, aes(x = rating)) +
  geom_bar()








# labs() defines/names the axes
ggplot(hikes, aes(x = rating)) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(x = "Rating", y = "Number of hikes")








# fill() allows you to change the color of the bars
ggplot(hikes, aes(x = rating)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "blue") +
  labs(x = "Rating", y = "Number of hikes")








# color allows you to change the color of the border around the bars
ggplot(hikes, aes(x = rating)) +
  geom_bar(color = "orange", fill = "blue") +
  labs(x = "Rating", y = "Number of hikes")








# theme_minimal() changes the background to simplest version?
 ggplot(hikes, aes(x = rating)) +
  geom_bar(color = "orange", fill = "blue")  +
  labs(x = "Rating", y = "Number of hikes") +
  theme_minimal()







Exercise 5: Bar Chart Follow Up
Part a
What’s the purpose of the +? When do we use it? We use it if we are trying to combine functions.
We added the bars using geom_bar()? Why “geom”? geometry/geometric - its creating a rectangle?
What does labs() stand for? The axes?
What’s the difference between color and fill? Color change the border/perimeter color of the bars and fill changes the color of the actual bar
Part b
Observed categories: What categories did we observe? Easy, moderate and difficult
Variability between categories: Are observations evenly spread out among the categories, or are some categories more common than others? Some are more common than others
Part c Is there anything you don’t like about this barplot? For example: check out the x-axis again. the x axis categories are ordered weirdly because they are in alphabetical order. Also the text font is also ugly.
Exercise 6: Sad bar chart
Among the hikes, what’s the range of elevation and how are the hikes distributed within this range (e.g. evenly, in clumps, “normally”)? The range of elevation is from ~3500 - ~5500ft. The elevations are in clumps, it is not normally or evenly distributed.
What’s a typical elevation? ~4300ft
Are there any outliers, i.e. hikes that have unusually high or low elevations? No, not really.
(These questions were answered after completing Exercise 9)
Exercise 7:A histogram of elevation
Histograms are constructed by:

dividing up the observed range of the variable into ‘bins’ of equal width; and
counting up the number of cases that fall into each bin.

Questions to consider

typical outcome: Where’s the center of the data points? What’s typical?
variability & range: How spread out are the outcomes? What are the max and min outcomes?
shape: How are values distributed along the observed range? Is the distribution symmetric, right-skewed, left-skewed, bi-modal, or uniform (flat)? outliers: Are there any outliers, i.e. outcomes that are unusually large/small?

Exercise 8: Building Histograms

ggplot(hikes, aes(x = elevation))







Exercise 9: Building Histograms Pt 2

# aes() defined the variable of interest as elevation and geom_histogram() defined how the data is being visualized
ggplot(hikes, aes(x = elevation)) +
  geom_histogram()

`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.









# the color argument allowed for separation between the bars of the histogram (creates a white border around the histogram bars)
ggplot(hikes, aes(x = elevation)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "white") 

`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.









# fill argument changes the color of the histogram bars.
ggplot(hikes, aes(x = elevation)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "white", fill = "blue") 

`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.









# labs() provides axes labels for the x and y axis
ggplot(hikes, aes(x = elevation)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "white") +
  labs(x = "Elevation (feet)", y = "Number of hikes")

`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.









# binwidth argument changes the width of the histogram bars along the x-axis.
ggplot(hikes, aes(x = elevation)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "white", binwidth = 1000) +
  labs(x = "Elevation (feet)", y = "Number of hikes")








# binwidth() again changes the width of the bars; here they are much narrower.
ggplot(hikes, aes(x = elevation)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "white", binwidth = 5) +
  labs(x = "Elevation (feet)", y = "Number of hikes")








# width of bars changed again
ggplot(hikes, aes(x = elevation)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "white", binwidth = 200) +
  labs(x = "Elevation (feet)", y = "Number of hikes")







Exercise 10: Histogram Follow-up

What function added the histogram layer/geometry?

The function geom_histogram() is responsible for adding the histogram geometry in the plot.

What’s the difference between color and fill?

- color: Refers to the color of the outline or border of the bars in the histogram.
- fill: Refers to the color that fills the interior of the bars.

Why does adding color = “white” improve the visualization?

Adding color = “white” improves the visualization by making the borders of the bars more distinct, creating a clearer contrast between bars and improving readability.

What did binwidth do?

Binwidth controls the width of the bins in the histogram. By adjusting it, you determine how much data each bin represents, impacting the granularity of the data distribution.

Why does the histogram become ineffective if the binwidth is too big (e.g. 1000 feet)?

If the binwidth is too large (e.g., 1000 feet), the histogram will become too generalized and fail to capture the finer details and variations in the data distribution. This results in a loss of insight.

Why does the histogram become ineffective if the binwidth is too small (e.g. 5 feet)?

If the binwidth is too small (e.g., 5 feet), the histogram will become overly fragmented, creating too many bins with sparse data in each. This makes it difficult to see the overall pattern and can lead to a noisy, misleading representation of the data.
Exercise 11: Density Plots
-Density plots are essentially smooth versions of the histogram.
-Instead of sorting observations into discrete bins, the “density” of observations is calculated across the entire range of outcomes.
-The greater the number of observations, the greater the density!
-The density is then scaled so that the area under the density curve always equals 1 and the area under any fraction of the curve represents the fraction of cases that lie in that range.

ggplot(hikes, aes(x = elevation)) +
  geom_density()







Exercise 12: Density Plots vs Histograms
-The histogram and density plot both allow us to visualize the behavior of a quantitative variable: typical outcome, variability / range, shape, and outliers.
-What are the pros/cons of each? What do you like/not like about each?

  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method="lm")

`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method="lm")

`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'








-Since median_rent showed a stronger and clearer relationship (less noisy, more points seem to be close to the line of best fit) with repub_pct_20 than median_age, it is the better predictor.
-This makes sense because rent often reflects economic factors, urbanization, and cost of living, which are typically stronger indicators of voting patterns than median age.
Exercise 6: Sad Scatterplot

#repub_pct_20 is quantitative, but historical is categorical.
ggplot(elections, aes(y = repub_pct_20, x = historical)) +
  geom_point()







Explain why a scatterplot might not be an effective visualization for exploring this relationship
A scatterplot is ineffective for visualizing relationships between a quantitative and a categorical variable because categorical data lacks a numeric axis (consists of groups rather than continuous numerical data), leading to overlapping points and poor pattern visibility.

- Color coding does not match the colors names of the different historical categories
- Plots are overlapping each other

  geom_density() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("blue", "purple", "red"))








# What does alpha = 0.5 do? Changes the opacity of the plots (made it more opaque)
# Play around with different values of alpha, between 0 and 1

  geom_density(alpha = 0.5) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("blue", "purple", "red"))








# What does facet_wrap do?! Splits the data into subplots for clearer view

  geom_density() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("blue", "purple", "red")) +
  facet_wrap(~ historical)

# Why is this terrible? It doesnt really separate the 3 categories into subplots like the facet funtion
ggplot(elections, aes(x = repub_pct_20, fill = historical)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "white") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("blue", "purple", "red"))

`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.








Exercise 10
Out of boxplots, violins, and stratified density plots
Which do you like best?
Boxplots and stratified density plots
What is one pro of density plots relative to boxplots?
Density plots allow for a more nuanced visualization of the data’s distribution. They can show the full shape, including areas where the data is more concentrated or sparse, helping to reveal features like skewness or bimodality that boxplots cannot.
What is one con of density plots relative to boxplots?
Density plots can be sensitive to bandwidth choices, meaning that the appearance of the plot can change based on how the data is smoothed. This can lead to misleading or overly complex representations, while boxplots are simpler and provide clear information about central tendency and spread without this sensitivity.
Exercise 11: Categorical vs Categorical – Intuition Check

# How are the "historical" and "winner_20" variables mapped to the plot, i.e. what roles do they play?
ggplot(elections, aes(x = historical, fill = winner_20)) +
  geom_bar()








# A faceted bar plot
ggplot(elections, aes(x = winner_20)) +
  geom_bar() +
  facet_wrap(~ historical)








# A side-by-side bar plot
# Note the new argument to geom_bar
ggplot(elections, aes(x = historical, fill = winner_20)) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge")








# A proportional bar plot
# Note the new argument to geom_bar
ggplot(elections, aes(x = historical, fill = winner_20)) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill")







Part a Name one pro and one con of using the “proportional bar plot” instead of one of the other three options.
Pro of using a proportional bar plot: Proportional bar plots are great for showing the relative sizes of categories within a whole, making it easier to compare the proportions of different categories across groups. This is especially useful when you want to emphasize the distribution of categories in relation to the total.
Con of using a proportional bar plot: Proportional bar plots can make it harder to compare absolute values, as they focus on percentages or proportions rather than actual counts. If you’re interested in the precise number of occurrences in each category, other types of bar plots (like side-by-side or stacked) might be more informative.
Part b What’s your favorite bar plot from part and why?
Faceted Bar Plot - because it is easied to look at the visualization when data is stratified as much as possible. It does not look crowded, overlapped or noisy.

Exercise 1: SAT Scores
Part A Construct a plot of how the average sat scores vary from state to state. (Just use 1 variable – sat not State!)

ggplot(education, aes(x=sat)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "white")

`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

  geom_density()







Part B Summarize your observations from the plot. Comment on the basics: range, typical outcomes, shape. (Any theories about what might explain this non-normal shape?)
-bimodal pattern
-major mode is at a frequency of 6 (this means that the sat score that happened the most frequent was ~900)
-minor mode is at a frequency of ~4 (second most common sat score is ~ 1050)
-uncommon to get an sat score in the 850s and 1100s
Exercise 2: SAT Scores vs Per Pupil Spending & SAT Scores vs Salarie
Part A

# Construct a plot of sat vs expend
# Include a "best fit linear regression model" (HINT: method = "lm")
ggplot(education, aes(x=expend, y = sat))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method="lm")

`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'









# Construct a plot of sat vs salary
# Include a "best fit linear regression model" (HINT: method = "lm")
ggplot(education, aes(x=salary, y=sat))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method="lm")

`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'








Part B What are the relationship trends between SAT scores and spending? Is there anything that surprises you?
-Expend - how much a state spends on education
-Salary - typical teacher’s salary
Both relationships follow the same trends. As the amount of money a state spends on education increases, there is a general decline in SAT scores. As the typical salary of teacher increases, we see a general decline in SAT scores. Pretty weird; did not expect that.
Exercise 3: SAT Scores vs Per Pupil Spending and Teacher Salaries Construct one visualization of the relationship of sat with salary and expend. HINT: Start with just 2 variables and tweak that code to add the third variable. Try out a few things!

  the data.

  variable into a factor?








Exercise 4: Another way to Incorporate Scale
Construct the plot below. Check out the code and think about what’s happening here. What happens if you change “2” to “3”?.

  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, method = "lm")

`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'








The cut() function groups the data
Describe the trivariate relationship between sat, salary, and expend.
There is a general decline overall in average SAT scores as salary and expenditure increases
Exercise 5: Finally an Explanation
Part A Build a univariate viz of fracCat to better understand how many states fall into each category. (the fraction of a state’s students that actually take the SAT.)

ggplot(education, aes(x=fracCat))+
  geom_bar()







Part B Build 2 bivariate visualizations that demonstrate the relationship between sat and fracCat. What story does your graphic tell and why does this make contextual sense?

ggplot(education, aes(x=sat, fill=fracCat))+
  geom_density()+
  facet_wrap(~fracCat)







Part C Make a trivariate visualization that demonstrates the relationship of sat with expend AND fracCat.

ggplot(education, aes(x= expend, y = sat))+
  geom_point()+
  facet_wrap(~fracCat)+
  geom_smooth(method="lm")

`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'








Highlight the differences in fracCat groups through color AND unique trend lines. What story does your graphic tell? Does it still seem that SAT scores decrease as spending increases?
Now we see a general increase in SAT scores as the amount of money spent on education and resources (expend) increases once we account for the fraction of a state’s students that actually take the SAT.
Part D Putting all of this together, explain this example of Simpson’s Paradox. That is, why did it appear that SAT scores decrease as spending increases even though the opposite is true?
Simpson’s paradox is a phenomenon in probability and statistics in which a trend appears in several groups of data but disappears or reverses when the groups are combined. In this case, we see that fraCat is a confounding variable. It skews the relationship between SAT scores and salaries/expenditure. Once we account for the proportion of students who actually take the SATs per state, it no longer skew the data.

(`geom_point()`).

Part a Calculate the total number of births in each month and year, eg, Jan 1969, Feb 1969, …. Label month by names not numbers, eg, Jan not 1. Then, plot the births by month and comment on what you learn.

Birthdays |>
  group_by(year, month) |>
  summarise(total_births = sum(births)) |>
  mutate(month_name = factor(month.abb[month], levels = month.abb)) |> # Convert month numbers to names (Jan), w/o levels = month.abb, months appear alphabet.
  ggplot(aes(x = month_name, y = total_births, group = year, color = factor(year))) + #allows for discrete colors per year instead of a gradient
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Total Births by Month and Year",
       x = "Month",
       y = "Total Births",
       color = "Year") +
  theme_minimal()

`summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
`.groups` argument.








Lowest total number of births in the year ~1975/6 Highest total number of births in the year ~1969 Overall, February has the lowest total number of births August has the overall highest number of births Each year follows the same general increase/decrease patterns throughout the months
Part b In 1988, calculate the total number of births per week in each state. Get rid of week “53”, which isn’t a complete week! Then, make a line plot of births by week for each state and comment on what you learn. For example, do you notice any seasonal trends? Are these the same in every state? Any outliers?

Birthdays |>
  mutate(week = week(date)) |> 
  filter(year == 1988, week != 53) |>  # Keep only 1988 and remove week 53
  group_by(state, week) |>
  summarise(total_births = sum(births)) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = week, y = total_births, color = state)) +
  geom_line(alpha = 0.7) +  # Transparency for better visualization
  labs(title = "Weekly Births by State in 1988",
       x = "Week of Year",
       y = "Total Births",
       color = "State") +
  theme_minimal()

`summarise()` has grouped output by 'state'. You can override using the
`.groups` argument.








Part c Repeat the above for just Minnesota (MN) and Louisiana (LA). MN has one of the coldest climates and LA has one of the warmest. How do their seasonal trends compare? Do you think these trends are similar in other colder and warmer states? Try it!

  mutate(week = week(date)) |> 
  filter(year == 1988, week != 53, state %in% c("MN", "LA")) |>  # Keep only 1988 and remove week 53
  group_by(state, week) |>
  summarise(total_births = sum(births), .groups = "drop") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = week, y = total_births, group = state, color = state)) +
  geom_line(alpha = 0.7) +  # Transparency for better visualization
  labs(title = "Weekly Births by State in 1988",
       x = "Week of Year",
       y = "Total Births",
       color = "State") +
  theme_minimal()

What stands out to you in these summaries? Is there anything you’d need to clean before using this data? Part a
Scalability: Handles large datasets more efficiently than spreadsheets.
Traceability: Keeps a record of each cleaning step for easy review.
Minimizing Human Error: Reduces risk of mistakes compared to manual edits.
Version Control: Enables tracking changes with Git for collaboration and rollback.
Integration: Seamlessly continues analysis without exporting data.
Consistency: Ensures the same cleaning steps are applied across all data.
Documentation and Sharing: Combines code and results in one reproducible file
